full_text(utf-8): b"Concerned because she knew Graves' Disease is no small thing, as I've already said. But, happy because she'd held me through my breakdowns when stressing about not knowing why I was so sick, and seeing I finally had an answer for it all."

full_text: "Thank goodness! Thank goodness, I finally know what's wrong with me! After all these years, I finally know why I'm so sick!" I messaged my sister as soon as I could see clearly again and told her about my diagnosis. She was happy for me, but also concerned.
full_text(utf-8): b'"Thank goodness! Thank goodness, I finally know what\'s wrong with me! After all these years, I finally know why I\'m so sick!" I messaged my sister as soon as I could see clearly again and told her about my diagnosis. She was happy for me, but also concerned.'

full_text: Still, I was so relieved to finally hear a diagnosis. I finally had a name for it. I could finally have the right help. I was so relieved about all of that, that as soon as the doctor left me in the room to seek out the head surgeon, I started to cry.
full_text(utf-8): b'Still, I was so relieved to finally hear a diagnosis. I finally had a name for it. I could finally have the right help. I was so relieved about all of that, that as soon as the doctor left me in the room to seek out the head surgeon, I started to cry.'

full_text:
I was finally put on medication that helps me. I finally had a plan for what was to happen next. I finally had an answer as to why I had been so sick.
I had suspected I had something serious, there was no way something minor would make me so sick. But, wow.
full_text(utf-8): b'I was finally put on medication that helps me. I finally had a plan for what was to happen next. I finally had an answer as to why I had been so sick.\nI had suspected I had something serious, there was no way something minor would make me so sick. But, wow.'

full_text: It's been a year since I received my diagnosis of Graves' Disease. After going years without proper help, with two hospital stays, multiple ER visits, doctors either accusing me of faking or just ordering the same blood tests again and again...I finally found out.

full_text:
I have shown him a couple of other anime that he conceded were not like Pokemon. Saiyuki Requiem for example. He kept calling Hakuryu a bird, but he's a dragon.
I also showed him an episode of Get Backers.

full_text: He wasn't a major fan, to the point of getting the DVDs or merch, but guess what he told me the weeks following... He watched it even when I wasn't there. I actually got my grandfather into Neon Genesis Evangelion!
full_text(utf-8): b"He wasn't a major fan, to the point of getting the DVDs or merch, but guess what he told me the weeks following... He watched it even when I wasn't there. I actually got my grandfather into Neon Genesis Evangelion!"

full_text: One night, Neon Genesis Evangelion (the old dub) was on TV. Pa let me watch it, and he soon joined me. It was hard to explain the concept, I just thought it was an interesting series at the age of 15. Well, he did learn not ALL anime is Pokemon.

full_text: And you know what? I felt validated by seeing her. I felt like my family was wrong, that I really could still enjoy anime as an adult. That I could attend conventions and wear my merchandise proudly. That even if I was still into it when I'm over 50, that's still okay.

full_text:
Loosely translated...
"He wasn't recorded in history because he didn't accept honours, he prefers to breathe in the fragrance of flowers and the evening air." He has never presented himself to the King and is always quick to leave when he knows rewards are being handed out.
full_text(utf-8): b'Loosely translated...\n"He wasn\'t recorded in history because he didn\'t accept honours, he prefers to breathe in the fragrance of flowers and the evening air." He has never presented himself to the King and is always quick to leave when he knows rewards are being handed out.'

full_text: Because of Albert preferring no medals and honours as rewards, he tends to work in the background, keeping an eye on things and throwing off the Cardinal's Guards and Milady de Winter if they try causing trouble.
full_text(utf-8): b"Because of Albert preferring no medals and honours as rewards, he tends to work in the background, keeping an eye on things and throwing off the Cardinal's Guards and Milady de Winter if they try causing trouble."

full_text: The original trio do find Albert's inventions to be amazing and love seeing them, as well as using them in action. Captain De Treville trusts Albert a lot and usually has him in charge of missions, and Albert is always eager to show him his new inventions.
full_text(utf-8): b"The original trio do find Albert's inventions to be amazing and love seeing them, as well as using them in action. Captain De Treville trusts Albert a lot and usually has him in charge of missions, and Albert is always eager to show him his new inventions."

full_text: He and D'Artagnan have somewhat of a brotherly bond, looking out for each other in their own ways. D'Artagnan is always praising Albert's inventions, and they work well together. This isn't to say he isn't close with the others, of course.
full_text(utf-8): b"He and D'Artagnan have somewhat of a brotherly bond, looking out for each other in their own ways. D'Artagnan is always praising Albert's inventions, and they work well together. This isn't to say he isn't close with the others, of course."

full_text: He gets along well with all of his fellow Musketeers, even if they sometimes cause him a bit of exasperation (they were "dumbed down" for comedic effect). He's especially close with D'Artagnan and is the one best at placating him when he loses his temper.
full_text(utf-8): b'He gets along well with all of his fellow Musketeers, even if they sometimes cause him a bit of exasperation (they were "dumbed down" for comedic effect). He\'s especially close with D\'Artagnan and is the one best at placating him when he loses his temper.'

full_text: His rewards are the satisfaction of a job well done, being able to relax in the countryside, spending time with an animal, enjoying some tea, finally completing the invention he was stumped on or reading a book.
full_text(utf-8): b'His rewards are the satisfaction of a job well done, being able to relax in the countryside, spending time with an animal, enjoying some tea, finally completing the invention he was stumped on or reading a book.'

full_text:
Of course, it sometimes has extra ingredients like extreme hot sauce (causes comedic fire breathing), quick-setting cheese or sleep powder. 
Albert is someone who is modest. The French version of the theme song explains it better in the final verse.
full_text(utf-8): b'Of course, it sometimes has extra ingredients like extreme hot sauce (causes comedic fire breathing), quick-setting cheese or sleep powder. \nAlbert is someone who is modest. The French version of the theme song explains it better in the final verse.'

full_text: Because of his stature, while he is skilled in sword fights and won't back down from them, he mainly uses his inventions to counter enemy attacks. His favourite is the Bolognese Blunderbuss. Basically, he uses spaghetti bolognese as ammunition.
full_text(utf-8): b"Because of his stature, while he is skilled in sword fights and won't back down from them, he mainly uses his inventions to counter enemy attacks. His favourite is the Bolognese Blunderbuss. Basically, he uses spaghetti bolognese as ammunition."

full_text: The song pretty much explains who he is. He's the smallest but the bravest and smartest of the Musketeers, standing at only 103cm including the feather in his hat and 20 years old. He is always coming up with inventions that aid him and his friends.

full_text: Because Natsuki is someone who has lots of love to give and he won't hold back. So, if you're special to him, he'll be sure to remind you every single day that he loves you so, so much!

full_text: But, he really does mean no harm. He loves his friends very, very much and he wants them to be happy. He wants to share what he can of himself to remind them that he cares for them. A hug, homemade cookies, some tea, kind words, his own time, he'll share them all with friends.
full_text(utf-8): b"But, he really does mean no harm. He loves his friends very, very much and he wants them to be happy. He wants to share what he can of himself to remind them that he cares for them. A hug, homemade cookies, some tea, kind words, his own time, he'll share them all with friends."

full_text: He might get a little overwhelming with those who he knows best, but it comes from a place of love. He wants to share his cooking and hugs because he loves his friends so, so much! They might cause problems (since his cooking leaves a lot to be desired unless you're Ren).

full_text: He's not afraid to speak his mind anymore, but he still does it in a way that is calm and soothing in order to ensure everyone around him is also able to calm down, like when Ranmaru and Eiichi kept fighting and his input allowed them to calm down and think.

full_text: He doesn't hold grudges against anybody. Remember when he was assigned to work with Nagi? Even though things had been antagonistic, he was still excited to work with him, greeted him with a hug and when all was said and done, still felt fondness for his duet partner.

full_text: I don't like considering these "special abilities" though. They're just new norms for me as someone who is disabled. At risk of falls, prone to weak days, prone to having to call an ambulance at a moment's notice, prone to hurting myself with every fall.
full_text(utf-8): b'I don\'t like considering these "special abilities" though. They\'re just new norms for me as someone who is disabled. At risk of falls, prone to weak days, prone to having to call an ambulance at a moment\'s notice, prone to hurting myself with every fall.'

full_text: On days I'm alone and having a weak day, I carry my phone with me just in case I have a really bad fall or something else goes wrong and I need help as fast as is possible. I can't exactly skip eating otherwise I'm at risk of ketoacidosis (even from 24 hours).
full_text(utf-8): b"On days I'm alone and having a weak day, I carry my phone with me just in case I have a really bad fall or something else goes wrong and I need help as fast as is possible. I can't exactly skip eating otherwise I'm at risk of ketoacidosis (even from 24 hours)."

full_text: It's fine if someone's home with me, if I am not able to move as much that day, Dad can help me with meals and I can be supported going to the toilet if need be. But, I am out of luck if Dad's at work and Pa's not available.
full_text(utf-8): b"It's fine if someone's home with me, if I am not able to move as much that day, Dad can help me with meals and I can be supported going to the toilet if need be. But, I am out of luck if Dad's at work and Pa's not available."

full_text: Oh, that's another "special ability" I have. Learning to identify those days. Do my legs feel weak even before I get out of bed? Are they shaky the second I'm standing? Do I have "exertion tremors" despite only sitting up? Then, I'd better be careful.
full_text(utf-8): b'Oh, that\'s another "special ability" I have. Learning to identify those days. Do my legs feel weak even before I get out of bed? Are they shaky the second I\'m standing? Do I have "exertion tremors" despite only sitting up? Then, I\'d better be careful.'

full_text: But, those can be costly as hell, I have nowhere else to store it and I don't need it ALL the time (as opposed to always needing my scooter if I leave the house on my own), only on the weak days.
full_text(utf-8): b"But, those can be costly as hell, I have nowhere else to store it and I don't need it ALL the time (as opposed to always needing my scooter if I leave the house on my own), only on the weak days."

full_text: My grandfather keeps suggesting I get a walking stick (that I can also take with me on my scooter and use to whack at any ne'er-do-wells), I keep thinking I'd be better with a walker like my great-aunt Gladys and my nan use to get around.
full_text(utf-8): b"My grandfather keeps suggesting I get a walking stick (that I can also take with me on my scooter and use to whack at any ne'er-do-wells), I keep thinking I'd be better with a walker like my great-aunt Gladys and my nan use to get around."

full_text: I'm a fortnight off from being 35. I shouldn't be working out how to safely handle a fall because I shouldn't be falling in the first place. I should be receiving proper support, which I was for a time but our time is up with the next appointment being the last.
full_text(utf-8): b"I'm a fortnight off from being 35. I shouldn't be working out how to safely handle a fall because I shouldn't be falling in the first place. I should be receiving proper support, which I was for a time but our time is up with the next appointment being the last."

full_text: Those "special abilities" can save me from being really hurt, can help make sure I only deal with new bruises that take a week or two to go away (depending on the hardness of the surface), but I'm not proud of having them.
full_text(utf-8): b'Those "special abilities" can save me from being really hurt, can help make sure I only deal with new bruises that take a week or two to go away (depending on the hardness of the surface), but I\'m not proud of having them.'

full_text:
All of the cracks are signs of the burden of everything I'm feeling threatening to break everything out from under me.
And of course, the person in the picture is me, crying and hugging myself, feeling alone and helpless.

full_text: The rain cloud is the depression and the feeling of "nothing will ever be okay". The waves are the pain coursing through my entire body (worse in my limbs) and the general feeling of being sick. The floor is the pit I'm falling into.

full_text: I did finally manage to get the exemption sorted out, but still! Just going shopping for clothes I'd have to wear on the job wore me out so much I needed two weeks of rest and was on "possible ambulance watch" because I was that sick.
full_text(utf-8): b'I did finally manage to get the exemption sorted out, but still! Just going shopping for clothes I\'d have to wear on the job wore me out so much I needed two weeks of rest and was on "possible ambulance watch" because I was that sick.'

full_text: It was either go on the dole, get the exemption (but I had to see a doctor for that, yet it was a time of the year appointments were hard and if I was already feeling sick I didn't want to go out) or lose my benefits. Those were my options.
full_text(utf-8): b"It was either go on the dole, get the exemption (but I had to see a doctor for that, yet it was a time of the year appointments were hard and if I was already feeling sick I didn't want to go out) or lose my benefits. Those were my options."

full_text: So, I couldn't take medicine and just power through the pain that can get so bad I am on my back, limbs in the air and screaming that I want them chopped off so I wouldn't have to feel such intense pain anymore. I looked half-dead as it was that day.
full_text(utf-8): b"So, I couldn't take medicine and just power through the pain that can get so bad I am on my back, limbs in the air and screaming that I want them chopped off so I wouldn't have to feel such intense pain anymore. I looked half-dead as it was that day."

full_text: What upset me though was hearing that. I wasn't on anything other than vitamin supplements, anti-depressants and the earlier days of taking ondansetron to control the nausea. I had nothing that could control all of the symptoms or even help me feel well enough.
full_text(utf-8): b"What upset me though was hearing that. I wasn't on anything other than vitamin supplements, anti-depressants and the earlier days of taking ondansetron to control the nausea. I had nothing that could control all of the symptoms or even help me feel well enough."

full_text:
I thought that maybe she might be able to sympathise. Nope.
"I have five conditions, but I still have to work, so I just take my medicine and push through the pain."
I wanted to cry for both of us. Nobody should have to push through!

full_text: Lin and Banba acknowledge that because they kill people, they're not exactly good people. But, they are still morally-grey on the scale because while they murder, it's often people who deserve it.

full_text:
The characters in the three series vary on the morality scale too.
Roberto and Hiraga are Catholic priests (appalled by what others have done to children) who are good people. They have their pasts, they have their methods, but they want to stay white on the scale.
full_text(utf-8): b'The characters in the three series vary on the morality scale too.\nRoberto and Hiraga are Catholic priests (appalled by what others have done to children) who are good people. They have their pasts, they have their methods, but they want to stay white on the scale.'

full_text: I find series like those intriguing, I love series that are dark but also have their light comedy and strong character bonds.
full_text(utf-8): b'I find series like those intriguing, I love series that are dark but also have their light comedy and strong character bonds.'

full_text: Roberto and Hiraga deepen their bond as partners with every new assignment, Lin finds he has a new family with Banba and the rest of the Ramens, and the Moriarty brothers pretty much have a bond forged by fire and blood after that night that changed everything.
full_text(utf-8): b'Roberto and Hiraga deepen their bond as partners with every new assignment, Lin finds he has a new family with Banba and the rest of the Ramens, and the Moriarty brothers pretty much have a bond forged by fire and blood after that night that changed everything.'

full_text: What stands out for all is that they have their lightly comedic moments but are over all dark and serious in tone but also focus on the strong bonds formed between the main characters.
full_text(utf-8): b'What stands out for all is that they have their lightly comedic moments but are over all dark and serious in tone but also focus on the strong bonds formed between the main characters.'

full_text: But, there were close calls and reminders that my illness was no small thing through the years. So, it was then that I started to do the countdowns. I would chose ten screenshots featuring treasured characters and put one up each day leading to my birthday.
full_text(utf-8): b'But, there were close calls and reminders that my illness was no small thing through the years. So, it was then that I started to do the countdowns. I would chose ten screenshots featuring treasured characters and put one up each day leading to my birthday.'

full_text:
After Pa had taken me to the doctor's clinic, he reminded me "your birthday is coming up, try to focus on that when you get too upset". So, I started to. 
Then, chronic illness set in. The first couple of years, not too bad, just spending it in bed.

full_text:

full_text: If I were to try to do more despite not having any PP left, I have to "use Struggle", as in push myself past an already set limit. Just as that hurts the Pokemon using it, it can make things worse for me and result in bad days ahead.
full_text(utf-8): b'If I were to try to do more despite not having any PP left, I have to "use Struggle", as in push myself past an already set limit. Just as that hurts the Pokemon using it, it can make things worse for me and result in bad days ahead.'

full_text:
So, I see it like this.
I have set PP for the things I can do in a single day. I use up some each time. (Longer activities mean the PP drops with each ten minutes.) I use all of them up, can't do them anymore.
full_text(utf-8): b"So, I see it like this.\nI have set PP for the things I can do in a single day. I use up some each time. (Longer activities mean the PP drops with each ten minutes.) I use all of them up, can't do them anymore."

full_text:
Basically, a Pokemon can use up to four moves. Each has a set number of PP, meaning the number of times you can use the move before it runs out and needs to be restored or won't be able to be used.
Once all moves lose PP, the Pokemon uses Struggle which hurts it.
full_text(utf-8): b"Basically, a Pokemon can use up to four moves. Each has a set number of PP, meaning the number of times you can use the move before it runs out and needs to be restored or won't be able to be used.\nOnce all moves lose PP, the Pokemon uses Struggle which hurts it."

full_text:
It just occurred to me that I can use Pokemon as a good descriptor for the Spoon Theory, like how some like using video games and MP as their explanation.

Why Pokemon? Because of how each move uses PP that runs out with each move.

full_text: So naturally, after eight years of that (Prep to Grade Six including my repeating Grade Five) practically every day, it hit that point that when I was a teenager, I could only respond the same way I did when I was 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11 and 12 - I cried.
full_text(utf-8): b'So naturally, after eight years of that (Prep to Grade Six including my repeating Grade Five) practically every day, it hit that point that when I was a teenager, I could only respond the same way I did when I was 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11 and 12 - I cried.'

full_text: Mostly because it happened far too often when I was still developing emotionally as a child. Not by my parents, I have been a lucky one without parental neglect. No, it was peers. Classmates. Other kids including those I thought were friends.

full_text: The first lesson is about invalidation and "choices of response that can affect how it affects the person in the future". But, all I can recall from every time I felt invalidated and rejected by peers was that my instantaneous response was to start crying.
